{
  "result": "To evaluate the integral \( I = \int_e^{e^2} \frac{\ln x - 1}{x^2} \, dx \), we can use integration by parts.

Let \( u = \ln x - 1 \), so \( du = \frac{1}{x} dx \).
Let \( dv = x^{-2} dx \), so \( v = -\frac{1}{x} \).

Using integration by parts formula:
\[ \int u \, dv = uv - \int v \, du \]

Compute \( uv \):
\[ uv = \left( \ln x - 1 \right) \left( -\frac{1}{x} \right) = -\frac{\ln x - 1}{x} \]

Compute \( \int v \, du \):
\[ \int v \, du = \int \left( -\frac{1}{x} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} dx \right) = -\int \frac{1}{x^2} dx = \frac{1}{x} \]

Putting it all together:
\[ I = -\frac{\ln x - 1}{x} \Big|_e^{e^2} + \frac{1}{x} \Big|_e^{e^2} \]

Evaluate at the bounds:
1. Compute \( -\frac{\ln x - 1}{x} \Big|_e^{e^2} \):
   \[ -\frac{\ln e^2 - 1}{e^2} + \frac{\ln e - 1}{e} = -\frac{2 - 1}{e^2} + 0 = -\frac{1}{e^2} \]

2. Compute \( \frac{1}{x} \Big|_e^{e^2} \):
   \[ \frac{1}{e^2} - \frac{1}{e} = -\left( \frac{1}{e} - \frac{1}{e^2} \right) \]

Combine the results:
\[ I = \left( -\frac{1}{e^2} \right) + \left( \frac{1}{e} - \frac{1}{e^2} \right) = \frac{1}{e} - \frac{2}{e^2} \]

Simplify with common denominator:
\[ I = \frac{e - 2}{e^2} \]

\(\boxed{\dfrac{e - 2}{e^2}}\)
"
}
